  "prompt": "Any good books to develop a statistical background? For a math major wanting to get more into stats",
  "response": "For a math major looking to delve deeper into statistics, there are several excellent books that cater to building a strong statistical foundation. Here are some recommendations:\n\n1. **\"Statistical Inference\" by George Casella and Roger L. Berger** - This is a comprehensive book that covers a wide range of topics in statistical theory and inference. It's well-suited for someone with a mathematical background and provides rigorous proofs and exercises.\n\n2. **\"All of Statistics: A Concise Course in Statistical Inference\" by Larry Wasserman** - This book provides a broad overview of statistical methods and is accessible to those with a solid mathematical foundation. It covers both the theoretical and applied aspects of statistics.\n\n3. **\"Introduction to the Theory of Statistics\" by Alexander M. Mood, Franklin A. Graybill, and Duane C. Boes** - A classic text that provides a rigorous introduction to statistical theory, suitable for students with a strong mathematical background.\n\n4. **\"Probability and Statistics\" by Morris H. DeGroot and Mark J. Schervish** - This book balances the rigorous development of probability theory with practical applications in statistics, making it suitable for math majors.\n\n5. **\"The Elements of Statistical Learning: Data Mining, Inference, and Prediction\" by Trevor Hastie, Robert Tibshirani, and Jerome Friedman** - While more focused on applied statistics and machine learning, this book provides insight into statistical methods used in modern data analysis, albeit it assumes a good understanding of linear algebra and calculus.\n\n6. **\"An Introduction to Probability and Statistics\" by Rohatgi and Ehsanes Saleh** - This book covers probability theory first and then moves on to statistical inference, making it a good choice for someone with a mathematical orientation.\n\n7. **\"Bayesian Data Analysis\" by Andrew Gelman, John B. Carlin, Hal S. Stern, and Donald B. Rubin** - If you're interested in Bayesian statistics, this is a leading text that covers both theoretical and practical aspects.\n\nFor someone with a strong mathematical background, these books will not only help in understanding the fundamental concepts of statistics but will also bridge the gap to more advanced topics in data science and applied statistics.",
